# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1886-philadelphia-athletics-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1885-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1885 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with a 55–57 record and finished in fourth place in the American Association.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1886 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 16th season of the franchise.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1886 Brooklyn Grays season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The team finished the season in third place with a record of 76–61 (their first winning season), 16 games behind the St.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1886 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 15th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 11th in the National League and the second at the first West Side Park.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished first in the National League with a record of 90–34, 2.5 games ahead of the second place Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was defeated four games to two by the St.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings lost the 1886 World Series to the St.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1886 Detroit Wolverines** had the best winning percentage of any major league baseball team to play in Detroit.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-detroit-wolverines-season] They compiled a record of 87–36 for a .707 winning percentage.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-detroit-wolverines-season] Nevertheless, the Wolverines finished in second place, 2½ games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1886-philadelphia-athletics-season/1886-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1886 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with a 63–72 record and finished in sixth place in the American Association.
